# About and replication/change details

## About: 
*	The website is written in Typescript (Javascript) and used Next.js to build it (Next.js allows for minimal setup, is quick and state-of-the-art. Alternatives might offer similar features, but often require additional configuration or third-party packages.) The website is static.

Some info about the website which will help with adding features and changing stuff:
*	I use a pretty standard modern frontend stack
1.	Typescript is used (tsconfig.json, .ts files)
2.	Tailwind CSS for styling (tailwind.config.ts + postcss.config.mjs)
3.	I use migrated npm from the pnpm package manager
4.	Shadcn/ui is the giveaway for the component library.
5.	Deployment: out/ .nojekyll are for static export (so no paid server needed). The .nojekyll file needs to be present to prevent GitHub from trying to process it with Jekyll.
 
## Replication/change: 

Hereby the instructions for updating the website:
 
Step 1: clone the POAL repo here laurencleek/POAL_website. You make all changes directly in this repo and can run  ‘npm run dev’ in the terminal to preview the website with the new changes you make.
 
Step 2: Once you are happy with the changes type ‘npm run build’ in the terminal and there will be a static render (takes about 1 minute). This creates a ‘out’ folder.
 
Step 3: log into the POAL github account and clone PublicOpinionAnalyticsLab/publicopinionanalyticslab.github.io. Once you have a local clone, add the entire ‘out’ folder content to this folder and override all folders already present. Then you can use the usual methods to push it onto github. These changes will appear about 5 min later (make sure to refresh the page). (I configured that the out folder compiles the necessary output to run the static website and that it automatically is all placed in the folder).
 
Common bugs: make sure to delete the Next and Out folders before you run ‘npm run dev’ or ‘npm run build’ otherwise error messages will occur. Remove the .next and out folder (either via cmd: `rm -rf .next out’) or manually. 
 

Basically, all changes are made in the app folder which I’ve neatly organised by page. So, each folder in this folder represents a static webpage. I have put all images, documents, etc. in the public folder. Directly making changes here is the easiest way to add features to the website without messing up the overall website.
 
